Licensing & credits
================================================================================

wise pdf is a 100% client-side (in-browser) PDF tool. Files are never uploaded;
all processing runs locally via WebAssembly. wise pdf does NOT include or
redistribute the source code of any of the libraries below — they are consumed
as npm dependencies (downloaded by the end user / bundled by the consuming app)
and are not vendored into this repository.

Runtime dependencies:

  - pdfjs-dist      Apache-2.0      https://github.com/mozilla/pdf.js
      Mozilla's PDF parser/renderer. Used to decode PDFs, render pages to a
      canvas at a chosen DPI, and read embedded image XObjects.
  - pdf-lib         MIT             https://github.com/Hopding/pdf-lib
      Used to build PDFs from images and to replace image streams in place.
  - @jsquash/jpeg   Apache-2.0      https://github.com/jamsinclair/jSquash
      WebAssembly build of mozjpeg (the codec itself is BSD-3-Clause). Used to
      re-encode images to JPEG at higher quality-per-byte than canvas.toBlob.
  - @jsquash/oxipng Apache-2.0      https://github.com/jamsinclair/jSquash
      WebAssembly build of oxipng (MIT/Apache-2.0). Used for lossless PNG output.
  - fflate          MIT             https://github.com/101arrowz/fflate
      Store-only ZIP packaging for multi-page "PDF to JPG" export.

Codec licensing of the paths wise pdf actually uses:

  - JPEG (re-encode)   : mozjpeg / libjpeg-turbo   BSD-3-Clause / IJG (permissive)
  - PNG  (lossless)    : oxipng / zlib             MIT / Apache-2.0 / zlib (permissive)

No GPL- or AGPL-licensed code is used. AGPL-licensed engines such as MuPDF and
Ghostscript were deliberately avoided so that wise pdf stays cleanly MIT and can
be freely redistributed. All code paths used by wise pdf are therefore under
permissive (MIT / Apache-2.0 / BSD / zlib) terms compatible with the MIT license
of this project.

Because these libraries are consumed as dependencies (not redistributed within
this repository), no additional redistribution obligations are imposed by this
project.
